    "Mitchell G. Reddish, Nijay K. Gupta": "Scholars have debated whether Adam `[char_Adam_Luk_3]` is in Paul `[char_Paul_Act_13]`\u2019s mind in the\nPhilippian Christ Hymn (2:5-11) as a counter-type to the humble and\nfully obedient Christ.\nMaking a connection between Christ and Adam `[char_Adam_Luk_3]` is of more than\n[v_1Co_15_45] passing interest for Paul `[char_Paul_Act_13]`. In 1 Cor 15:45 he refers to Adam `[char_Adam_Luk_3]` as \u201cthe\nfirst man\u201d (ho pr\u00f8tos anthr\u00f8pos) and Christ as \u201cthe last Adam `[char_Adam_Luk_3]`\u201d (ho\neschatos adam). He does not compare the two as complete equals.\nThe first man was merely a \u201cliving being,\u201d a creature. The last Adam `[char_Adam_Luk_3]`\n[v_1Co_15_45] is a \u201clife-giving spirit\u201d (1 Cor 15:45). The first man was from earth,\n[v_1Co_15_47] the second from heaven (1 Cor 15:47). The\nkey reason, though, that the two can be\ncompared and contrasted is because they\nare molds that set forth a pattern. Adam `[char_Adam_Luk_3]`\nwas \u201cof dust,\u201d so those that are from him\nare also \u201cof dust.\u201d So also, Christ is the\nman from heaven, so those who identify\nwith him are heavenly (15:48).\nOne of the key indicators of how impor-\ntant this comparison is comes in 1 Cor\n15:22: \u201cFor just as in Adam `[char_Adam_Luk_3]` all die, so also\nin Christ all will be made alive.\u201d Notice the\nreference to humans being \u201cin Adam `[char_Adam_Luk_3]`.\u201d This\nis the only time Paul `[char_Paul_Act_13]` uses this language,\nbut it contrasts with \u201cin Christ,\u201d a phrase\nthat is a Pauline hallmark. Paul `[char_Paul_Act_13]`\u2019s whole the-\nological framework revolves around\nbelievers being freed from the hegemony\nof slavery under sin and death as they live\n\u201cin Adam `[char_Adam_Luk_3]`,\u201d meaning something like \u201cin the\nage of Adam `[char_Adam_Luk_3]`.\u201d Now they belong to Christ\nand aim to \u201cbear the image of the man of\n[v_1Co_15_49] heaven\u201d (1 Cor 15:49).\nCranach, Lucas the Elder.\nAdam `[char_Adam_Luk_3]`."
